As indicated in the previous section, there is a strong need to expand access to unambiguous, evidence-based abortion information to women and providers. However, even when information is readily available to women, providers, and social service providers, contextual factors may nonetheless result in the stigma and subsequent devaluation of the knowledge. Our respondents highlighted factors within the multiple systems, namely provider systems, healthcare systems, and societal systems, that prohibit the free exchange of information on abortion.
Systemic stigma is a central reason that data are siloed and providers do not share particular medical information:
You should ask why data about abortions are not collected by reproductive health workers. Well, for us, lawyers, when and why we talk about them; stigma and many other things are at play. They are persecuted, they are disobeyed…especially, those who carry out abortions, if they don’t have four witnesses, they could only get one year in prison. [29] –Legal mosaician-Social Dr. Njonke uses terms like “partof,’ “piece,” “skirmish,” and “those who carry act abortions” to refer to individuals for whom information, including reputable, evidence-based abortion information, must remain confidential.
